WSB-DT went on the air on April 17, 1998, making it one of the first regular-service [[digital television]] stations in the country (the -DT suffix is not mandated by the FCC, thus it is WSB-TV even for digital). The over-the-air [[digital subchannel]] 2.2 started carrying the [[Retro Television Network]] on January 28, 2008.<ref name="abizc">{{cite news|title=TV classics come to WSB with RTN|author = ''[[Atlanta Business Chronicle]]''|date=2007-11-20 |accessdate=2007-12-12|publisher = [[American City Business Journals]], Inc. |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2007/11/19/daily13.html?t=printable}}</ref> Prior to this, the channel was [[dead air|blank]], or later with a small [[station ID]] in the lower corner. RTV programming was replaced with Me-TV on June 1, 2011.

WSB-TV also has a [[mobile DTV]] feed of subchannel 2.1, labelled "WSB MH", broadcasting at 1.83 Mbit/s.<ref>[http://www.rabbitears.info/market.php?request=atscmph]</ref><ref>[http://www.mdtvsignalmap.com/ Mobile DTV Signal Map from the National Association of Broadcasters]</ref>

===Analog-to-digital conversion===
Don McClellan, celebrating 50 years at the station, shut down the station's analog signal for the last time on June 12, 2009 at 12:30 p.m., during a [[remote broadcast|live broadcast]] from the station's [[transmitter plant|transmitter room]] on the noon newscast, as part of the [[Digital television transition in the United States|digital television transition]]. The station's digital signal remained on [[Ultra high frequency|UHF]] channel 39.<ref name="FCCForm387">[http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/forms/prod/cdbsmenu.hts?context=25&appn=101231057&formid=387&fac_num=23960 CDBS Print<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> It uses [[Program and System Information Protocol|PSIP]] to display WSB-TV's [[virtual channel]] as 2 on digital television receivers.

During late August and into September 2009, the station removed its analog [[Television transmitter|transmitter]] from the top of the tower, and moved its side-mounted digital antenna up from its previous lower location on the tower.

