In March 2009, the station filed applications for two digital fill-in [[broadcast translator|translator]]s (both of which also carry the WSB-TV callsign), due to expected loss of signal strength toward the east and northeast of Atlanta as a result of the shortcomings of the [[ATSC]] digital broadcast standard. The station's [[Gainesville, Georgia|Gainesville]]-[[city of license|licensed]] translator broadcasts on UHF channel 46, and began operations on June 26. It is located on the same [[radio tower]] as Cox's [[WSRV (FM)|WSRV]] FM and [[WSBB-FM]], and reaches as far into Atlanta's north-northeastern [[suburb]]s as [[Lilburn, Georgia|Lilburn]]. The [[Athens, Georgia|Athens]]-licensed translator broadcasts on UHF channel 31, with its transmitter located southwest of [[Winder, Georgia|Winder]], and its signal also reaches as far west as Lilburn. WSB-TV requested [[special temporary authority]] to begin immediate operation of these stations, pending approval of its regular applications.

The [[broadcast range|signal coverage]] of both stations largely overlap with one another, and are almost entirely within the estimated coverage area of the main station, however [[distributed transmission]] ([[co-channel|on-channel]] [[Repeater#Usage|boosters]]) will not be used. The translators are intended to overcome the terrain obstructions caused by [[Stone Mountain]] to the east of the WSB transmitter, and were in operation by January 2011. The Athens station uses virtual channels 2.5 and 2.6 instead of 2.1 and 2.2, while the Gainesville station uses 2.7 and 2.8, allowing viewers to choose whichever station whose signal is better receivable at a given time (certain [[ATSC tuner]]s may have trouble with two stations using the same virtual channel, and even if not, the user would have to enter the channel number and press "channel-up" or "channel-down" buttons to access the alternates, which would not be separately labeled or identified by the tuner).

In late June 2009, the station also applied for a translator on channel 14 just southwest of [[Rome, Georgia|Rome]]. That translator would cover a significant portion of [[northwest Georgia]] from the same tower as [[WQTU (FM)|WQTU]] (102.3 FM) and [[WSRM (FM)|WSRM]] (93.5 FM), and the same site as [[WGPB (FM)|WGPB]] (97.7 FM), [[W212AR]] (90.3 FM), and [[W215BA]] (90.9 FM).<ref>[http://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?type=0&list=1&dist=1&dlat2=34&mlat2=14&slat2=2&dlon2=85&mlon2=13&slon2=50&size=10]</ref> There is no STA request for this station however, and {{as of|2011|September|lc=on}} it is still listed as only an application. In October 2010, WSB-TV applied for and later received a [[construction permit]] for another translator southwest of Atlanta in [[Newnan, Georgia|Newnan]] on channel 17. This translator will be co-located on the same tower as Cox-owned [[WALR-FM]] (104.1), and less than {{convert|.25|mi|km}} west of another tower holding [[WBZY (FM)|WBZY]] (105.3 FM; which is not owned by Cox).<ref>[http://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?type=0&list=1&dist=1&dlat2=33&mlat2=24&slat2=43&dlon2=84&mlon2=50&slon2=3&size=10]</ref>

==News operations==
[[File:WSB open.png|thumb|right|210px|WSB nightly newscast open.]]
WSB-TV presently broadcasts 41 hours of locally produced newscasts each week (with six hours on weekdays and Sundays, and five hours on Saturdays); as such, WSB-TV is one of the few [[Big Three television networks|Big Three]] network affiliates to offer more than 35 hours of local news content each week and one of the few Big Three affiliates to carry a midday newscast on weekends. In addition, WSB-TV's weekend newscast output is larger than that of Fox owned-and-operated station [[WAGA]] (channel 5), which offers a larger overall weekly (and weekday) newscast output than WSB-TV. Appropriately for a station with roots in a newspaper, local news programming has had a strong presence on channel 2 since its debut, and it has led the news [[audience measurement|ratings]] in Atlanta for as long as records have been kept.

One factor behind its dominance is talent continuity, as many of the station's personalities have been on the air for 15 years or more. Monica Pearson (known as Monica Kaufman until 2005) had been the station's top anchorwoman since 1975, and was one of the first African-American female anchors in the South. Starting in 1994, her co-anchor had been John Pruitt, who started at channel 2 in 1973 before beginning a 16-year run at WXIA. Glenn Burns has been the main weatherman since 1981. Chuck Dowdle served as the station's [[sports director]] from 1985 until his retirement in December 2009. Pearson, Pruitt, Burns and Dowdle served as WSB's main anchor team from Pruitt's return to Channel 2 in 1994 until 2010 <U+2013> longer than any news team in Atlanta. On December 17, 2010, Pruitt retired from WSB-TV after 46 years in the business; this was followed two-and-a-half years later by Pearson's retirement on July 25, 2012, after a 37-year career.

WSB-TV became the second station in the Atlanta market (behind [[WXIA-TV]]) and the second Cox-owned station (behind [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]]'s [[WFTV (TV)|WFTV]]) to begin broadcasting its local newscasts in [[High-definition television|high definition]], on September 27, 2006 during its noon broadcast. With the switch came a new HD-ready set and a graphics package designed by [[Giant Octopus (company)|Giant Octopus]].

In mid-November 2009, reporter Tom Jones and a cameraman escaped serious injury when the [[telescopic cylinder|telescoping]] [[radio mast]] of their [[electronic news-gathering]] van (holding a [[microwave]] [[television antenna|antenna]] for the [[remote pickup unit]] used for [[outside broadcasting]]) contacted 115-[[kilovolt]] [[high-voltage]] [[Overhead power line|powerlines]] while leaving the [[Fulton County Jail]]. [[Georgia Power]] staff were surprised that anyone survived, but the two were treated for minor burns and [[smoke inhalation]] at [[Grady Memorial Hospital]] and released later in the day. The massive [[electric spark]] caused an explosion, left a [[Explosion crater|crater]] underneath the van, arced to and broke a water main, and caused a brief [[power outage]]; the vehicle was a [[total loss]].<ref>[http://broadcastengineering.com/eng/archive/news-photog-reporter-escape-injury-eng-van-accident-112409/ News photographer, reporter escape serious injury in ENG van accident], ''Broadcast Engineering'', November 24, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.ajc.com/news/wsb-tv-employees-survive-203866.html WSB-TV employees survive truck explosion], ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'', November 18, 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.tvtechnology.com/feature-box/0124/tv-eng-van-explodes/204092 TV ENG Van Explodes], ''TVTechnology'', November 19, 2009.</ref>

In July 2010, WSB-TV expanded its weekday morning newscast to 2<U+00BD> hours, with the start time moved to 4:30 a.m. It announced a news partnership with [[Telemundo]] affiliate [[WKTB-LD]] on August 23, 2010.<ref name=ajc-wktbwsb>{{cite news|title=Channel 2 WSB-TV, Telemundo in partnership|url=http://www.ajc.com/business/channel-2-wsb-tv-597602.html|accessdate=July 2, 2011|newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=August 23, 2010}}</ref> On May 26, 2011, WSB-TV debuted an hour-long 4 p.m. newscast, which replaced ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show|Oprah]]'' when the daytime talk show ended its 25-year run.<ref>[http://www.tvnewscheck.com/article/2010/11/23/47241/wsb-atlanta-announces-4-pm-newscast/ WSB Atlanta Announces 4 P.M. Newscast], TVNewsCheck.com. Retrieved 11-23-2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.wsbtv.com/station/27673991/detail.html Channel 2 Action News at 4 Launches May 26]</ref>

