* [[Stu Klitenic]] - sports anchor/reporter (1989<U+2013>1996; now Atlanta Braves Radio Network post-game anchor)
* [[Toni Neal]] - traffic reporter (2003<U+2013>2005; now at [[Microsoft]])
* [[John Palmer (TV journalist)|John Palmer]] - anchor/reporter (1960<U+2013>1962; retired from [[NBC News]] in 2002)
* [[Byron Pitts]] - reporter (1994<U+2013>1996; now with [[ABC News]])
* [[Hal Suit]] - anchor/news director (1948<U+2013>1978; former Republican candidate for [[Governor of Georgia]] in 1970)<ref>[http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=23007]</ref>

==Out-of-market coverage==
Unlike the co-owned ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'', WSB-TV has not abandoned service to outlying counties. In [[northwest Georgia]], it is carried in the counties covered by the [[Chattanooga]] DMA: [[Catoosa County, Georgia|Catoosa]], [[Dade County, Georgia|Dade]], [[Murray County, Georgia|Murray]], [[Walker County, Georgia|Walker]] and [[Whitfield County, Georgia|Whitfield]]. WSB is also carried in the far [[northeast Georgia]] counties in the [[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]/[[Spartanburg, South Carolina|Spartanburg]]/[[Asheville]] DMA in [[Elbert County, Georgia|Elbert]], [[Franklin County, Georgia|Franklin]], [[Hart County, Georgia|Hart]] and [[Stephens County, Georgia|Stephens]] counties.

In [[central Georgia]], WSB-TV is available to subscribers of co-owned cable provider [[Cox Communications]] in the [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]] area, although ABC programming is usually [[blackout (broadcasting)|blacked out]] by another local ABC affiliate, [[WGXA-DT2]]. Given the long distance to Middle Georgia, it is likely that WSB-TV is [[uplink]]ed to the [[AMC-10]] [[satellite TV|TV satellite]]. WSB is also carried in [[Vidalia, Georgia|Vidalia]] in the [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]] DMA.

In south Georgia (as far south as the [[Florida]] border), it is carried on Cox Communications systems due to a historical lack of an ABC affiliate in the [[Albany, Georgia|Albany]] [[media market]] covering [[southwest Georgia]]. Since the market's NBC affiliate [[WALB]] began carrying ABC on its 10.2 [[digital subchannel]] in 2010, [[blackout (broadcasting)|blackout]]s for syndicated programming have become common. Given the long distance to South Georgia, it is likely that WSB-TV is [[uplink]]ed to the [[AMC-10]] [[satellite TV|TV satellite]]. [[Charter Communications]] also carries WSB for its subscribers in the town of [[Douglas, Georgia|Douglas]] in [[Coffee County, Georgia|Coffee County]].

In [[western North Carolina]] it was previously carried in the [[Cherokee County, North Carolina|Cherokee County]] town of [[Murphy, North Carolina|Murphy]], alongside [[Asheville, North Carolina]] ABC affiliate [[WLOS]].

